From: Sergey Fedorov <barracuda@macos-powerpc.org>
Date: Sun, 19 Jul 2026 19:02:05 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 36/67] =?UTF-8?q?fix(macos):=20set=20the=20engine's=20cell?=
 =?UTF-8?q?=20pixel=20size=20=E2=80=94=20sixel=20freeze?=
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

Screen::sixelImage() derives the image's grid height as
ceil(imageHeightPx / cellPixelSize().height). Terminal::_cellPixelSize
defaults to {0,0} and is only populated by resizeScreen() when a pixel
size is passed. The macOS session never seeded it: the constructor sizes
the renderer but never calls setCellPixelSize(), and resizeScreen() only
runs on an actual window resize (resize() early-returns when the size is
unchanged). So before the first resize the cell height is 0.

Displaying a sixel in that state divides the image height by 0, yielding an
astronomically large line count; renderImage() then tries to scroll that
many lines through the 1000-line scrollback, each scroll reallocating a
blank SoA line. The parser thread grinds on this for effectively forever
while holding _stateMutex, so the render thread blocks in fillRenderBuffer
and the UI shows the spinning ball — a deterministic "freeze" on the first
sixel, independent of image byte size (the cost scales with the bogus row
count, not the data).

Seed _cellPixelSize from the renderer's grid metrics (the authoritative
cell size, same value the render probe uses) in the constructor, before any
sixel can arrive, and pin it again after each resize since resizeScreen()'s
surfacePixels/totalPage derivation drifts from the true font cell size by
the page margin and rounding.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.8 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>
Claude-Session: https://claude.ai/code/session_01AeG2jwYMX5gdvvtUnx3PJa
---
 src/contour_macos/TerminalSession.cpp | 12 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+)

diff --git a/src/contour_macos/TerminalSession.cpp b/src/contour_macos/TerminalSession.cpp
index 5e464f98..4528544c 100644
--- a/src/contour_macos/TerminalSession.cpp
+++ b/src/contour_macos/TerminalSession.cpp
@@ -85,6 +85,15 @@ TerminalSession::TerminalSession(vtbackend::PageSize pageSize,
     _renderTarget.setRenderSize(surfaceSize);
     _renderer.applyResize(
         surfaceSize, _pageSize, vtrasterizer::PageMargin { PageMarginPx, PageMarginPx, PageMarginPx });
+
+    // The engine needs the pixel size of a single cell to place pixel-addressed images (sixel,
+    // the good-image protocol). Screen::sixelImage() derives the image's grid height as
+    // ceil(imageHeightPx / cellPixelSize().height); if cell height is left at its default 0 the
+    // division yields an astronomically large line count and renderImage() then tries to scroll
+    // that many lines through the scrollback — a hard "freeze" on the first sixel. The Qt frontend
+    // sets this from its display layout; here the renderer's grid metrics are the authoritative
+    // cell size. Seed it now (before any window resize) and keep it current in resize().
+    _terminal->setCellPixelSize(_renderer.gridMetrics().cellSize);
 }
 
 TerminalSession::~TerminalSession()
@@ -165,6 +174,9 @@ void TerminalSession::resize(ImageSize newSurfaceSize)
     _renderer.applyResize(
         newSurfaceSize, _pageSize, vtrasterizer::PageMargin { PageMarginPx, PageMarginPx, PageMarginPx });
     _terminal->resizeScreen(_pageSize, newSurfaceSize);
+    // resizeScreen() derives cell size from surfacePixels/totalPage, which drifts from the true
+    // font cell size by the page margin and rounding. Pin it to the renderer's authoritative value.
+    _terminal->setCellPixelSize(_renderer.gridMetrics().cellSize);
 }
 
